Hi Patricia,

That’s a very interesting point. There definitely does need to be more education on cinematography within the industry. It can also be a problem from secondary schools. We are lucky to get some GCSE students on our film club productions, as a few schools within Salford have a Brathay Centre initiative. For me it’s been about getting started on my own learning outside of school. Filmmaking is such a broad subject, it’s important to find a representative film industry, or style that you feel suits your vision as a director. Once you find your medium it’s just about making more. You won’t be jumping into the film industry unless you already have a few projects under your belt and can back up your work with experience.

One filmmaker that plays is Christopher Nolan. Like many film directors making his big break happened when he made a low budget film called ‘Following’. Outside of education it’s rare that the film makers of blockbuster films were able to just make their films without experience.
